fields.bio: Hanin Ghaddar is the Managing Editor of NOW - English, where she has written on Lebanese and regional politics. She contributes regularly to a number of magazines and newspapers, including The New York Times and Foreign Policy. She has been a Public Policy Scholar at the Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars (Fall 2012). The fellowship involves a research project on Arab women after the Arab Uprisings and the rise of the Islamists. She comments on Hezbollah, the Shia community, Syria and Iran. Prior to joining NOW Lebanon in 2007, Ghaddar wrote for Assafir, Annahar and Al-Hayat and also worked as a researcher for the UNDP - regional office between 2002 and 2004. Ghaddar holds a Bachelor's degree in English Literature and a Master's degree in Middle Eastern Studies, both from the American University in Beirut

fields.bio: Until recently, I was Director of Programs at the Egyptian Center for Public Policy Studies (formerly the Egyptian Union of Liberal youth), a Cairo-based organization seeking to promote Classical Liberalism in Egypt. I studied Philosophy at Ain Shams University in Cairo and the Social Sciences at the University of Chicago. I was a 2008 Robert L. Bartley fellow with the Editorial Board of the Wall Street Journal. In 2011, I was awarded the Albert Einstein Fellowship by the Einstein Forum in Potsdam, Germany, and the Daimler-Benz Foundation. My writings have appeared in     the Wall Street Journal, the Weekly Standard, the Jewish Review of Books, Tablet Magazine, and Hudson Institute’s Current Trends in Islamist Ideology. Ali Al-Ahmed is a scholar and expert on Saudi political affairs including: terrorism, Islamic movements, Wahhabi Islam, Saudi political history, Saudi-American relations, and the al-Saud family history. He is a writer, and public speaker on Saudi political issues.

He has been invited to speak by Princeton University, Amnesty International, the Hudson Institute and Meridian International Center.

As journalist he exposed major news stories such as the Pentagon’s botched translation of the 9-11 Bin Laden tape, and the video of Daniel Pearl’s murder.

He has authored reports on Saudi Arabia regarding religious freedom, torture, press freedom, and religious curriculum.

fields.bio: Mina Abdelmalak was born and raised in Egypt. He received a law degree from Ain Shams University and studied non-violence and advocacy strategies at the Arab Academy for Non-Violence Studies. He worked as a legal researcher for the Egyptian Union of Liberal Youth (EULY), a Cairo-based, non-profit organization, which promotes classic liberalism among Egyptian youth. He supervised a program within EULY on the status of Coptic Christians in Egypt. In 2011 Mina moved to the U.S. and he now works at the United States Holocaust Memorial Museum as an outreach specialist.

fields.bio:
Freedom Now is a U.S.-based non-profit, non-governmental, and non-partisan organization that works to free individual prisoners of conscience through focused legal, political and public relations advocacy efforts.

Prisoners of conscience are persons detained for their political, religious, or other beliefs or because of their ethnic origin, sex, sexual orientation, color, language, national or social origin, economic status, birth or other status—who have not used or advocated violence.

fields.title: Help Syrian Women
fields.details: Syrian women have been at the forefront of the Syrian uprising during the first few months, but they have been sidelined by the armed rebellion, violence and the rise of the Islamists. These women did not go back to the private sphere but shifted their activities to aid work and media. It is essential to help Syrian women be prepared to take part of the political transition in Syria, whenever a political solution is reached, and encourage them to participate in the political process. This entails both a clear strategy/policy by all countries willing to help, and establishing proper channels to provide women with tools, starting now, so they are better prepared when they're needed. I have worked on this topic as my research project at the Woodrow Wilson Center in DC in the Fall of 2012 and I would like to follow it up in practical terms, for example, meeting with policy makers in DC to discuss best strategies, discuss it in the US media to raise awareness. Placing articles in major western publications would help. Meanwhile, provide Syrian women with tools and training, especially those who are still working in the field.

fields.title: The Plight of Mawaleed in Saudi Arabia
fields.details: One of the most underreported issues in Saudi Arabia is the plight of Millions of Saudi born sons and daughters of immigrants, known as Mawaleed, who have been living there for generations without any recognition or special treatment for their assimilation and adaptation of the culture and tradition. The first media attention this issue received was in 2010 when I launched an online forum where thousands of them rushed to register and share their stories, hopes and dreams of obtaining citizenship or at least permanent residency so that they at least wouldn’t be deported to countries they are only related to by name. After the launching of the forum a number of opinion writers have written dozens of articles in which they expressed their support to their plights and recommended that they be granted citizenship as they are a important element of the Saudi society.

fields.title: Seeking help in deploying Web-based public opinion survey in Cuba
fields.details: Greetings.  I am currently at work on a research project that seeks to investigate the beliefs and opinions of ordinary Cuban citizens related to their news media (radio, newspapers, TV, the Internet) and the news media of other countries to which they (might) have been exposed.  I've spent time in Cuba, meeting with both Cuban and American government officials, and Cuban media scholars, and journalists.  Now, I'm hoping to identify someone who can help me recruit approximately 100 people, with some (racial, gender and age) diversity to take an *online* survey that seeks to understand the credibility of the state-run media within Cuba, and any desire for economic and social reform within the Cuban media system.  I understand internet access is limited in Cuba and so this isn't an easy feat.  The survey, which is still in development, will be written in Spanish and should take 15 minutes to complete.
